Headlines.Headline: Indonesia free-fall sparks Asia sell-off

PARAGRAPH.#text:
HONG KONG (AP) -- Spooked by a record fall in Indonesia's currency, stock
    markets across Southeast Asia dropped sharply Thursday as investors liquidated portfolios.
    
    
    Indonesia's rupiah plunged 26 percent and its stock market suffered a 12 percent drop--
    both one-day worsts -- while Singapore shares hit a 5-year low and Philippine shares a
    4-year low. 
    
    There was good news in South Korea, where the main share index rose 3.6 percent due to
    strong buying demand from foreign investors. Foreigners, now allowed under new laws to own
    up to 55 percent of listed South Korean companies, snapped up shares of Korea Electric
    Power Corp., LG Electronics Inc. and Daewoo Telecom Co. 
    
    And in Tokyo, the yen strengthened slightly against the U.S. dollar due to expectations
    that the Bank of Japan might intervene to support the currency while senior Finance
    Ministry official Eisuke Sakakibara visits Washington this week. After climbing above 134
    yen early this week, to its highest level in more than 5 1/2 years, the dollar retreated
    to 133.01. 
    
    Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange were little changed. The Nikkei index fell 0.06 percent
    to 15,019.18.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Indonesia free-fall sparks Asia sell-off
